International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Tue 6 Jul 2010
Source: The Japan Times [edited]
<http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20100706a5.html>


Salivating cow spurs Miyazaki to kill 16 more
---------------------------------------------
Another cow in the city of Miyazaki was found to have symptoms of
foot-and-mouth disease [FMD], including excessive salivation, the
prefecture said, prompting officials to kill and bury 16 cows at the
farm as of Monday [5 Jul 2010] morning.

With the 1st suspected case since 18 Jun 2010, the prefecture will
have to delay its plan to declare an end to the outbreak of the
disease among livestock in Miyazaki to 27 Jul 2010 at the earliest,
instead of 16 Jul 2010.

"It's extremely regrettable," Gov. Hideo Higashikokubaru said at a
meeting called to consider countermeasures. "We will all work on the
matter once again by thoroughly investigating the suspected infection
route."

The case was found on a farm about 800 meters [0.5 mi] from the
facility hit by the last suspected case on 18 Jun 2010, prefectural
officials said. The cow in question was determined through
photographs as possibly being infected with the disease [see also
item 2 below].

The prefecture lifted some restrictions last Thursday [1 Jul 2010],
including a directive to postpone public events, in areas other than
those under livestock movement restrictions, after completing the
destruction of about 276 000 pigs and cows.

The decision remains unaffected by the new case, the governor said,
because the farm is located inside the area where livestock movement
is already restricted.

The prefecture was testing livestock with a view to lifting
restrictions on city traffic on 11 Jul 2010, with plans to declare on
16 Jul 2010 an end to the outbreak that began in April [2010].

Health officials have culled livestock within a 10-km [6.2 mi] radius
of farms in the town of Kawaminami and other municipalities where
many pigs and cows were found to be infected. The farm hit by the
latest case is not in the area covered by the measure.

Under farm ministry rules, 21 days must pass in principle after the
last destruction of livestock suspected of FMD before curbs are lifted

