[2]
Date: Mon 5 Jul 2010
Source: The Mainichi Daily News [edited]
<http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20100705p2a00m0na004000c.html>


New suspected foot-and-mouth case found in Miyazaki, lift on
restrictions delayed
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A new suspected case of FMD has been found at a farm here, causing a
delay in the much-awaited lifting of restrictions on livestock
movement and transport in the prefecture.

The Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries and the Miyazaki
Prefectural Government announced the suspected case on 5 Jul 2010.
All of the farm's 16 cows have already been slaughtered and buried.

This is the 292nd case of FMD in the prefecture, following a case
confirmed at another farm in Miyazaki on 18 Jun 2010. As no outbreaks
of the disease had been confirmed in the prefecture since then, the
prefectural government had been planning to lift livestock movement
and transport restrictions across the prefecture on 16 Jul 2010. Due
to the newly confirmed case, however, the restrictions are expected
to stay in place until at least 27 Jul 2010.

At the newly affected farm on 30 Jun 2010, blood samples were taken
from 9 cows to test whether they had been infected by the virus.
Because 3 of them failed an antibody test, prefectural government
officials visited the farm for a re-examination and found another cow
that had tested negative earlier drooling and having other FMD
symptoms. The Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries then
determined from photographs that the cow could be infected. [See
commentary below].

"It's extremely unfortunate and we take it seriously," Miyazaki Gov.
Hideo Higashikokubaru said during a task force meeting of his
government on 5 Jul 2010.

The prefectural government had on 1 Jul 2010 just lifted a suspension
on the holding of public events in the prefecture, except in areas
where the livestock movement and transport was restricted, since it
was thought the risk of infections was nearly gone.

